{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is an algorithmic quality bound of the routing heuristic itself. The real failure boundary is inside route-construction/route-scoring logic, not external I/O. A deterministic in-memory test with fixed coordinate sets and known optimal lengths can catch regressions.","test_description":"Call the heuristic function directly with a curated corpus of stop-coordinate fixtures (including adversarial layouts) and compare produced route length to precomputed optimal length per fixture. Assert ratio <= 1.5 for each case (up to 20 stops), and fail with ratio details.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is in deterministic math/config lookup (time = distance/speed plus window accumulation), which is a local logic boundary. No OS/network/subprocess behavior is required to expose incorrect calculations.","test_description":"Invoke the time-estimation function with explicit segment distances and road types plus a speed configuration map. Verify per-leg travel times and resulting windows match expected values, including rounding/units edge cases and mixed road types.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a pure validation rule over already-computed totals. The real bug is local threshold/excess arithmetic (comparison direction, units, or off-by-one), not module wiring.","test_description":"Test the validator function with route total durations and remaining shift hours around the boundary (below, equal, above). Assert rejection only when total exceeds remaining and assert returned excess duration is exact.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.005,"Agentic":0.003,"Workflow":0.002}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure mode is at module boundaries: geocoding-result handling, filtering, downstream optimizer input, and reporting output must stay consistent. A unit test of only one function can miss cross-module contract bugs.","test_description":"Run the service with a stubbed geocoding adapter that returns valid coordinates for most addresses and an explicit no-results response for one. Assert the failed address is listed in skipped-report output, absent from optimizer input, and final route contains only successfully geocoded stops.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior spans normalization + item aggregation + routing input/output. Real failures often come from wiring gaps (dedup applied but aggregation lost, or aggregation works but route still includes duplicates), which requires multi-module verification.","test_description":"Execute the service with repeated identical addresses carrying distinct delivery items. Assert output has one stop for that address, delivery items are merged correctly, and route visit sequence contains that stop exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
